{{Infobox artwork | image_file = Eagle by A.Calder.jpg | painting_alignment = Front | image_size = 300px | title = Eagle | alt = | other_language_1 = | other_title_1 = | other_language_2 = | other_title_2 = | artist = Alexander Calder | year = 1971 | type = sculpture | height_metric = | width_metric = | length_metric = | height_imperial = 38 | height_inch = 9 | width_imperial = 32 | length_imperial = 32 | length_inch = 6 | metric_unit = m | imperial_unit = ft | city = Seattle, Washington | museum = | coordinates = {{coord|47.61655|-122.35587|region:US-WA_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | owner = [[Seattle Art Museum]] }} '''''Eagle''''' is an [[abstract sculpture]] by [[Alexander Calder]].<ref>[http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=132Q2P908361A.14805&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!334708~!1&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=eagle&index=.GW&uindex=&oper=&term=calder&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1 "Eagle, (sculpture)"]. ''SIRIS''</ref> It is located at the [[Olympic Sculpture Park]], [[Seattle]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/07/21/arts/inside-art-calder-s-eagle-lands-in-seattle.html | title=INSIDE ART; Calder's 'Eagle' Lands in Seattle | work=The New York Times | date=July 21, 2000 | accessdate=January 2, 2012 | author=Vogel, Carol}}</ref>
==History== [[File:Calder the eagle at bank one fort worth.jpg|thumb|Calder ''Eagle'' original site at Bank One in Fort Worth.]] It was located at the Bank One building, 500 Throckmorton Street, [[Fort Worth, Texas]]. It was commissioned by Fort Worth National Bank. It was constructed in 1971 of painted sheet steel. It was erected, and dedicated on February 15, 1974. It was relocated in 2000 after being purchased by the [[Seattle Art Museum]] with funding from Jon and Mary Shirley. <ref>{{cite web | url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20000719&slug=4032550 | title=Calder's `Eagle' purchased for Olympic Sculpture Park | work=Seattle Times | date=July 19, 2000 | accessdate=January 2, 2012}}</ref>
