'''''The Fall of the Titans''''' is an [[oil painting]] of the [[Titanomachy]] by the Dutch painter [[Cornelis van Haarlem]] in 1588–1590. It measures {{nowrap|239 × 307 cm}} {{nowrap|(94 × 121 in)}}. The work is in the collection of the [[Statens Museum for Kunst|Statens Museum]] (the national art gallery) in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. It is an ambitious work of the [[Haarlem Mannerists]], and a display of the artist's ability to devise and depict a large number of varied poses for the male nudes.<ref>Statens</ref>
In [[Greek mythology]], the [[Titan (mythology)|Titans]] were members of the second generation of divine beings, descending from the [[Greek primordial deities|primordial deities]] and preceding the [[Twelve Olympians#Olympians|Olympians]]. Based on [[Mount Othrys]], the Titans most famously included the first twelve children of [[Gaia]] (Mother Earth) and [[Uranus (mythology)|Uranus]] (Father Sky). They ruled during the legendary [[Golden Age]], and also comprised the first [[Pantheon (gods)|pantheon]] of Greek deities.<ref>Statens</ref>
Just as the Titan [[Cronus]] overthrew his father Uranus, the Titans were overthrown by Cronus's children (Zeus, Hades, Poseidon, Hestia, Hera and Demeter), the core Olympian deities, in the [[Titanomachy]] (or "War of the Titans"), at the end of which they were imprisoned in [[Tartarus]], a Greek version of [[Hell]]. Their arrival there is depicted in the painting.
The painting was bought by King [[Christian IV of Denmark]] in 1621, and followed most of the royal collection into public ownership in the Statens in the 19th century.<ref>Statens</ref>
